## Escalation Logic (How It Works)

Escalation is based on **time and visibility**, not severity alone.

- Risk severity determines **whether action is required**  
- Time determines **when leadership is involved**

Example:

- A high-risk issue with active progress → no escalation  
- A medium-risk issue overdue by 30 days → Board visibility  

This ensures:
- focus on execution, not just scoring  
- early visibility of delivery failure  
- consistent treatment across risk categories  

---

## Integration with Risk Governance

This tracker is reviewed:

- Weekly by the GRC function  
- Monthly at Executive Risk Review  
- Quarterly at Risk Committee  

Board reporting includes:

- Number of overdue actions  
- Actions overdue >30 days  
- Actions linked to high-risk items (residual ≥ 9)  

---

## Failure Mode This Prevents

This tracker exists to prevent a specific failure:

> Risks are identified, documented, and accepted — but the actions required to manage them are not completed.

This is the failure mode observed in the Databridge incident.

---

## Ownership

| Role | Responsibility |
|------|--------------|
| Action Owner | Deliver action by deadline |
| Head of GRC | Maintain tracker; enforce escalation |
| CRO / COO | Resolve escalated delays |
| Risk Committee | Oversight of persistent non-delivery |

---

## What This Tracker Is Not

This is not:
- a project management tool  
- a task list  
- a reporting form  

It is a governance control.

> If actions are not completed, risk is not being managed — regardless of how well it has been documented.

